; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no coherent strategy to develop national and regional cycle routes that cross political boundaries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Responsibility for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycling schemes has been devolved to a lower level (County Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Committees) than road schemes (County C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ouncil). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a result, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">road schemes are being put fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rward without a cycling element -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sometimes resulting in worse cycling infrastructure.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Expectations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have been raised that local decision-making would direct money more effectively to the needs of cyclists, but as the rest of this response demonstrates, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implementation in West Sussex has largely dashed those expectations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Devolving transport decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s makes it almost impossible to plan and deliver non-local transport infrastructure, even on the scale of inter-urban </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycleways</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">neighbouring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> towns [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1].</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Transport is by its nature a very network-oriented issue, so changes in one location can ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve big impacts on another location: but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">localised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> transport spending doesn't allow this to be taken into account at all [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2]. Transport-specific planning and design knowledge is lost, as local councils do not have the expertise and experience in transpo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rt planning matters [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Examples - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[1] A county </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">councillor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from Lancing would like to build a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycleway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> between Lancing and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to benefit Lancing residents. However most of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycleway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will be within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing's</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> boundary, so he has to persuade </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">councillor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to promote his </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycleway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, even though it has much less value to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residents. This means that it's unlikely to ever happen; even though there is local community need and desire.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&gt; [2] The A27 through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is likely to become </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significantly more congested when the improvements at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Handcross</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Hill on the A23 are completed, making it much easier to drive to the south coast from Gatwick and further north. If the Arundel bypass </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were ever to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> built, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would lead to significant incre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ases in congestion in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from traffic finding it easier to drive along the A27 to and from the west. The A27 at Southampton is significantly more congested since the M3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Twyford</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Down cutting opened.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&gt; [3] Local officials recently placed a sharp-edged </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dark-blue sculpture in the middle of National Cycle Network Route 2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycleway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in Lancing. The local officers involved were unaware of the importance of this route, or the number of people on bicycles using it daily to commute to and from work. One officer w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as even unaware that the cycle route was continuous to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, even though it had been so for some years!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; bor