gh, or a disti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nct and separate rural area.   The great weakness of the current system is that local government at the County level has been subjected to cutbacks and seemingly constant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rationalisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. redundancies and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reorganisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).   This has created disconti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nuity and a certain amount of corporate paralysis.   There seems to be no overarching coherent policy that requires urgency to deliver it.   For example - there is evidence that S106 money is held up by bureaucracy.   There are no longer budgets allocated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to specific means of transport which means that - for example, cycle schemes that might deliver real benefit don't get </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as part of a core transport policy - more as a fringe and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> form of transport; although the talk in public is diffe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rent.   The CLC process is incapable of dealing with the volume that should go through its hands.   Consequently, those schemes that are easy to understand and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">quickly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decide on - get the vote.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Apart from benefitting from some isolated serendipitous schem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es, West Sussex County Council has not made any serious attempt to implement its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local Plan Transport Plan 3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (LTP3) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and has, similarly, made no attempt to replace it with anything else.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This, therefore, poses the question ‘what is the point of all of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effort put in to these plans if the Council has no mechanism to support it or implementing it?’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To answer the question - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local bodies do not have the capacity to assess, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prioritise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and deliver local transport schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The optimum delivery body is one th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at considers and values the economic, health and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">social benefits of sustainable transport, and incorporates those benefits into an integrated policy with a 'golden thread' running through transport, health, social and economic development policies.   It sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould consult with, and take 'on the ground' information from, those who know the locality.   Those consulted should be involved in the roll out of schemes.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local bodies (district and borough councils) are inconsistent in their approach to sustainable tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ansport. Decisions made by the county council in allocating funding to sustainable transport are not backed-up by, and are even contradicted by, decisions of Council Local Committees. The co-ordination of cycle schemes at county council level has been aban</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">doned with the abolition of the West Sussex County Council Cycling Officer and although there is someone doing his best to work with local cycle and sustainable transport groups, the fact is that he has another full time job that takes all his time.</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; b